SUBFAMILY PONERINAE
TRIBE PLATYTHYREINI
Platythyrea
Platythyrea are best distinguished by the small tooth on the pretarsal claws, but absent a good microscope, they are also recognizable by their lack of erect hairs and long, rectangular body shape. Wilson and Taylor (1967) noted that Platythyrea parallela is widespread but not abundant in Polynesia, and indeed my only collection of it in Micronesia was when a specimen fell on me in a restaurant.
Platythyrea parallela (Smith, F. 1859) Ponera parallela Smith, F. 1859
